                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok, Unmei. I took the bait. I usually don't do this cause it gets nowhere and its a waste on time IMO, but here it goes...
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">was it an unjustified nerf?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
Yes. 
<br />

<br />
Level 64 CoD charm works following the same principals it has always done from the begining of EQ. Nothing on the mechanics of the Charm line was changed with the introduction of level 64 CoD charm. Thus, CHARM was WORKING AS INTENDED, and was NOT broken.
<br />

<br />
What happened was that people got good at it and stopped dying so much, THEN people starting whinning about how much AA exp Chanters were getting when COMPARED to then. 
<br />

<br />
There didn't seem to be a problem with charm back in the days of Sebilis. Again, CHARM foundations have not been changed since the beginning of EQ days, thus in my view it was "working as intended" as it always was, no changes whatsoever were done in the CHARM line. 
<br />

<br />
What changed was SoE's lack of imagination lead to offering new content based on the simplistic "meaner mobs, uberest yet items" principle. And meaner mobs = higher DPS. How is that the chanters fault all of the sudden? They didn't say anything about Mages, apparently enough of them died while solo charming in BoT to satisfy the masses.
<br />

<br />
The basis of the nerf was people's envy, not fixing a bug on the charm line, and based on that whether you agree or not, it was unjustified (it was a decision made based purely on politics).
<br />

<br />
This same line of argument aplies to bard AEing. SoE did not all of the sudden go "Ooops, we meant bard AEs to only kill 4 mobs".  It was again working as intended, and only after people's complains of bards killing such number of mobs while they could only kill one at a time (and SINCE the dang bard is NOT dying... how dare the bard! He must pay for killing more mobs than I can!) that SoE took away Extended Notes from any damaging spell. 
<br />

<br />
I</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> could make the arguement that necros didn't need another solo tool (charm) and that necro charm is still viable in a group under many circumstances, but no one has ever seemed willing to listen to that possbility, because, ya know, why would a necro group?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Hmm... where outside CoD zone can a necro charm a level 60+ mob again?
<br />

<br />
Sure, charm is the least of the problems when it comes to necros. If you would visit the necro's forums more often you would have thought twice before throwing the "why would a necro group?" statement so lightly. 
<br />

<br />
The problem with necros is mainly that, although this has been fixed as of late to some extend, when grouping mobs die too fast for dots to do a decent amount of damage (perception is changing lately and people is starting to look at necros as a DPS class more now). Therefore, their utility is severely underminded by the fact that there simple are NO undead mobs outside of 1 or 2 zones. If necros could be slower/mezer substitutes in 40% of the zones, they would not gain 3+ AAs soloing with LFG up for countless hours while waiting on a group invite, only to finally camp out of boredom (as I have done in no few ocassions with my Necro).
<br />

<br />
You may say "Nerf (or as you put it "Balance") other classes group oriented abilities so that a necro has the same group desirability as any other class"
<br />

<br />
I say "Revamp 40% of the zones, or have a stupid undead invasion storyline (see: Grob, Trols and frogs) so that at least 40% of the high end mobs are undead"
