                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Class balance... it will never happen.  It can't happen because part of the equation is the person behind the toon, and everyone has different strenghts and weaknesses.
<br />

<br />
Life is not balanced either, if it were then there would be no need for so many things that go on day to day, year to year, century to century.  Life is not fair, nothing is fair.  Why should you expect a game to be fair?
<br />

<br />
Calling for the reduction in power, abilities, and playability of a class is bad form.  There will always be those who do better than others, no matter how "balanced" a situation is, be it in a RPG, a MMOG, board game, school, job, or life in general.  You cannot "nerf" something to make things for yourself better.  The best way to take care of imagined shortcomings is to find a work around to beat them, or to ask for a reasonable improvement that will benefit your own situation.
<br />

<br />
If you think EQ isn't just like Real Life, think again.  You are in competition against others, just as in real life.  You are seeking to improve yourself, just as in real life.  You are interacting with others, just like you do in real life; though not necessarily as you would face to face.
<br />

<br />
To me, those who call for nerfs are akin to the bullies in school, nothing more.  They want to feel they have power over you, to control you.
<br />

<br />
Just somethings to consider, ponder, think about.
<br />

<br />
No matter what any of us here say, it ultimately won't change anyones' mind on the subject.  Might as well be shadowboxing.  <img src="images/smiles/boxer.gif" alt="boxer.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />

<br />
Swarm kiting: taking a group of social mobs and charming one to get it beat down to near death by the rest of the social group and breaking charm before it dies and then DoT it down for XP, rinse and repeat.
<br />

<br />
Charm kiting: charming one mob to assist in killing another mob; you all ready should know this one.
<br />

<br />
AE kiting(spell type): getting a group of mobs and killing them with an AE nuke, takes lots of running a way and recasting and only hits 4 mobs at a time.
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: blue">PBAoE kiting(point blank AE-Bard AE): gathering up large numbers of mobs and settling them into a nice tight pack, twisting 3 to 4 PBAoE songs with the 2.5min Selo's thrown in much of the time.  This requires absolute attention to detail, lay out, mob mele ranges, obsticals, and other players who come too near.  Among the biggest danger here is other players "helping" thinking the bard is in trouble.  Rooting or snaring any single or bunch of the kite is absolutely deadly to the bard; some do this on purpose out of spite.  Other danger, again, is other players thinking they are going to "pull" a mob from the kite.  This usually ends in the whole kite taking out its vengence upon the unlucky KS'er, rarely does the bard die in this case, but it's a pain to get the kite back on track.  Notice that these 2 are purely player induced dangers.  A bard, even without other character interaction, faces enough danger in such a kite; why add to the dangers?</span>
<br />

<br />
Thought I'd share.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
